\intbl \ql \b Background\b0 \line The Academic Institute of Excellence is registered with the Department of Higher Education and Training as a private higher education institution and has programmes accredited by the CHE.\line \line The Institution applied for accreditation of the Bachelor of Science in Information Technology \'28contact mode\'29 which was tabled at the AC meeting held on the 28th of September 2022 and HEQC meeting held on the 4th of November 2022.\line \line The programme was not accredited for the following reasons\'3A\line 1. There are critical weaknesses in the programme design and the programme is not aligned with the purpose of a BSc in IT\'3A\line 1.1 There is a lack of alignment between the exit level outcomes\'2C and module outlines\'2C regarding the module title\'2C purpose statement\'2C assessment criteria and module content in most of the modules for this programme.\line 1.2 In the SAQA application\'2C there are 47 exit level outcomes with associated assessment criteria which raises concern regarding the Institution\'27s capacity to articulate meaningful exit level outcomes and to design programmes accordingly.\line 1.3 The application indicates that the programme comprises 47 modules totalling a minimum of 360 credits at NQF level 7\'3B however\'2C the 360-credit qualification comprises 17 compulsory modules plus 10 electives\'2C equating to 27 modules. The suite of 47 modules includes the elective modules comprising 10 modules per specialisation.\line 1.4 There is a lack of clarity on the rules of combination\'2C and which modules are offered in semester 1 and 2\'2C respectively.\line 1.5 Many of the co-requisites are inappropriate\'2C e.g. for \'27IT Project Management\'27\'2C and there appears to be a lack of understanding that co-requisite modules are offered concurrently with other modules.\line 1.6 There is a lack of clarity on why certain prerequisites have been identified\'2C e.g. \'27Software Development Fundamentals\'27 as prerequisite for \'27Systems Analysis and Design\'27.\line 1.7 The allocation of 20\'25 learning time to face-to-face lectures in a contact mode programme is inadequate.\line 1.8 There is a lack of alignment between the books listed in the module outlines and composite book list provided. Many books are outdated.\line 2.1 There is a lack of clarity about whether students must have Mathematics or Math Literacy for admission.\line 2.2 The marketing strategy does not provide adequate information on the qualification\'2C nor does it clarify the mode of provision of the programme.\line 2.3 There is a lack of clarity regarding the number of candidates to be admitted via Recognition of Prior Learning.\line 2.4 There is a lack of clarity regarding the number of years allowed for a student to complete the programme which is indicated as per discretion of the Principal and HOD.\line 3.1 No workload allocation has been provided nor is there an indication of how many modules a lecturer will be teaching.\line 3.2 The CV of the Principal indicates that the staff member is in full-time employment elsewhere.\line 3.3 There is a lack of clarity on how many hours per week are allocated per module considering that 20\'25 of time is allocated to face-to-face lecturing \'28which is inadequate for a contact programme\'29.\line 3.4 There is a lack of clarity on the mode of provision as the Institution uses the terms \'27contact\'27 and \'27distance\'27 in the application. In addition\'2C there is also reference to a \'27hybrid\'27 campus\'3B full-time\'2C virtual\'2C part-time\'2C and distance students. \line 4.1 The information in the application is not aligned with the institutional policies\'2C e.g. the allocation of teaching hours.\line 4.2 There is a lack of clarity regarding who will be responsible for programme management.\line 4.3 There is a lack of clarity on the workload allocation and whether a module leader will be responsible for contact and\'2For distance mode of delivery.\line 4.4 There is a lack of clarity on where the programme will be managed from\'2C i.e. Midrand or Cape Town.\line 4.5 The technical support identified in the programme is inadequate.\line 4.6 It is unclear what administrative support staff would be appointed to manage examinations\'2C registration\'2C graduation and capturing of marks.\line 5.1 There is a lack of clarity on the roles and responsibilities of e-tutors\'2C lecturers and facilitators.\line 5.2 There is a lack of clarity on how the same lecturers will teach at both sites of delivery.\line 5.3 It is unclear how at-risk students will be identified\'2C and who will be responsible for administrative matters related to these students.\line 6.1 There is a lack of clarity on formative and summative assessment per module.\line 6.2 The weighting of the formative assessments is excessive\'2C i.e. 60\'25 and summative exams 40\'25.\line 6.3 There is a lack of clarity on the method of assessment. Whilst there is brief reference to the use of continuous assessment in the application\'2C there is no reference to this method of assessment in the module outlines.\line 6.4 There is a lack of clarity on summative assessment regarding venue-based and online exams.\line 6.5 The assessment and moderation policy is inadequate for higher education\'3B insufficient information is provided in the policy in respect of moderation\'2C assessment procedures and process.\line 6.6 There are inadequate rules relating to supplementary examinations and no indication of \'27DP\'27 requirements for students to qualify to write exams.\line 6.7 There is a lack of clarity on the processes in place to ensure validity of results\'2C processing of results or responsibility for the capturing of results.\line 7. On both sites\'3A\line 7.1 There are insufficient venues for practicals.\line 7.2 The library facilities are inadequate and there is a lack of clarity regarding the availability of computers in the library for student use.\line 7.3 There is no evidence of network or cybersecurity laboratories for simulation nor is there information on the equipment required in these labs.\line 7.4 It is said the classrooms will be equipped but there is a lack of clarity regarding computers in these classrooms.\line 7.5 There is no indication of venues to be used for sit-down exams.\line 7.6 Students are required \'22to have or obtain a computer meeting specified minimum standard\'22\'2C however\'2C there is a lack of clarity what this standard would be.\line 7.7 There is a lack of clarity on whether the Institution will provide any resources for student practical work. \line 8.1 The Institution has not provided sufficient technical details relating to its systems.\line 8.2 The programme does not have effective administrative services for providing and managing the programme information system.\line 8.3 There are insufficient fields for student information to be captured and the types of reports are inadequate.\line 8.4 There is a lack of clarity on how the Management Information System will be used\'2C and who will be responsible for capturing\'2C quality assuring\'2C and signing off on marks.\line 8.5 There is a lack of clarity on whether the locus of responsibility for final sign-off of students\'27 marks will be in Midrand or Cape Town. \line \line NOTE TO THE INSTITUTION\'3A\line \'28i\'29 The policy on staff development is not adequate for a higher education institution.\line \'28ii\'29 The policy on staff recruitment does not cover sufficient information relating to legal compliance or minimum requirements for recruitment.\line \line The Institution submitted a representation which has been evaluated.\cell \pard 

