\intbl \ql \b Summary of Evaluator Report\b0 \line A summary of the evaluation follows below.\line \line 1.1 Alignment\'3A\line \line The Institution has provided subject forms divided according to the level of specialisation. There remains a challenge with the assessment criteria as they are formulated as subject learning objectives. The Institution needs to clarify the types of assessment included in the continuous assessment. Insufficient information has been provided. The reason has not been met.\line \line 1.2 Exit level outcomes\'3A\line \line The problem with the learning outcomes in this representation is that\'2C in many cases\'2C they do not correspond to the associated assessment criteria. The 47 exit level outcomes do not support the achievement of the intended purpose of the programme. The suggested exit level outcomes are for the compulsory subjects and the electives for the three specialisations. The 47 exit level outcomes do not relate to the relevant assessment criteria in most cases. Insufficient information has been provided. The reason has not been met.\line \line 1.3 Programme structure\'3A\line \line The Institution has submitted the programme structure\'2C module design and learner guides as revised documents. It has given students an option to study a module either through contact mode or distance mode learning. This is not possible as the submission is for a contact mode programme\'2C not distance. Hence\'2C giving an option to study in distance mode is not in line with the application. The subject forms need review on the assessment criteria and the continuous assessment tasks. Insufficient information has been provided. The reason has not been met.\line \line Reasons 1.4\'2C 1.5 and 1.6 Rules of combination\'3A \line \line The Institution has recreated the structure\'2C with the rules of combination\'2C with prerequisites and co-requisites. It has removed the prerequisite on the IT Project Management subject. On many other subjects there are no prerequisites. The Institution has removed the \'27Software Development Fundamentals\'27 as prerequisite for \'27Systems Analysis and Design\'E2\'80\'99. Still\'2C the Institution needs to explain why Office Solutions Development \'28OFSD111\'29 is co-requisite for Database Fundamentals.\line The reason has not been met.\line \line 1.7 Allocation of learning time\'3A\line \line The Institution has indicated that it has updated the learning time to 40\'25 for contact mode and 20\'25 for block sessions. Annexure D was not found in the representation files\'2C and it is difficult to see how the changes reflect the new total learning time. Insufficient information has been provided. The Institution needs to explain the shortage on learning time.\line \line 1.8 Book list\'3A\line \line The Institution indicates that a new book list has been developed with current titles that are aligned to the new structure\'2C module outlines and learner guides. Insufficient information has been provided. It is difficult to assess whether the changes have been applied or not. The reason has not been addressed.\line \line 2.1 Mathematics\'3A\line \line The Institution has provided an explanation on the admission requirements by stating that students with a National Senior Certificate \'28NSC\'29 should have a minimum of 50\'25 in either Mathematical Literacy or Mathematics. For students with foreign qualifications there is no requirement for Mathematics or any other subject.  This needs to be confirmed to avoid uncertainty in the admission process. The Institution should be specific on the admission requirements\'2C and this applies to the required subjects and their ratings as Mathematical Literacy cannot have the same requirements as Mathematics. There is no evidence provided which indicates how the Institution has updated the information. The reason has not been adequately addressed.\line \line 2.2 Marketing information\'3A\line \line The Institution has indicated that\'2C in the first submission\'2C it provided a holistic approach to marketing for the programmes that were already accredited. The fact sheet for this programme is not accessible. Insufficient information has been provided. The reason has not been addressed.\line \line 2.3 RPL\'3A\line \line The Institution has indicated provision will be made for 10\'25 of students registering as the first year cohort to be admitted through RPL. The RPL policy has not been submitted. The reason has not been adequately addressed.\line \line 2.4 Maximum duration \'2F completion\'3A\line \line The Institution has indicated that the amount of time required to complete the qualification is double its duration\'2C which is equal to six years. There was no policy document submitted to confirm this. It was not indicated which measures would be taken if students do not comply. The reason has not been addressed.\line \line 3.1 Workload\'3A\line \line The Institution has referred to an annexure which was supposed to contain its recruitment plan. This annexure was not submitted. The reason has not been met.\line \line 3.2 Principal\'27s CV\'3A\line \line The Institution has indicated that an incorrect version of the CV was uploaded\'3B and a new version has been uploaded. This CV does not indicate that the relevant person is currently employed by the Institution. The reason has not been addressed.\line \line 3.3 Hours per week\'3A\line \line The Institution has changed the learning time from 20\'25 to 40\'25. A 10-credit module will have four periods per week and 20-credit modules will have eight periods \'28hours\'29 per week. The Institution has referred to an annexure which is not in the submission. There is no policy addressing this. There is a need to make the teaching period allocation per credit part of institutional policy. The reason has not been met.\line \line 3.4 Mode of provision\'3A\line \line The Institution has justified the offering of the programme in contact and distance modes to increase the number of graduates who could be employable. If this is the case\'2C the Institution would need to submit full justification of its distance offering mode and it be accredited. In the absence of justification for the distance mode\'2C the current submission is for contact mode. Therefore\'2C the Institution is confusing the hybrid learning environment with a distance and contact mode\'2C and  cannot offer a distance mode programme if not accredited. The reason has not been addressed.\line \line 4.1 Teaching hours\'3A\line \line The response from the Institution is not pointing to the allocation of teaching hours\'2C which is the example provided in the reason. It is\'2C therefore\'2C clear that the Institution did not take time to respond to all the requirements. The Institution did not specify the sections of the updated policies and other information. Therefore\'2C the reason was not addressed.\line \line 4.2 Programme management\'3A\line \line The review of the CV shows that the Head of Department has a BScHons \'28Computer Information Systems\'29. However\'2C the employment history shows that from 1 January 2021 to present the HOD has been working for CTU Training Solutions as National Operations Manager. It is not clear when he was employed by the Institution. The reason has not been addressed.\line \line 4.3 Workload\'3A\line \line The ratio of 30\'3A1 is not an indication of workload as one lecturer cannot lecture 30 students from the beginning to the end of an academic year. As the programme is not yet offered\'2C it is a common understanding that academic staff members are currently lecturing other subjects. The annexure which was supposed to show more detail on the required number of full-time\'2C part-time\'2C and distance learning staff members\'2C was not submitted with the representation. The reason has not been addressed.\line \line 4.4 Location of programme\'3A\line \line The Head of Department will oversee the programme as the programme manager will be based in Midrand. In its response\'2C the Institution has indicated that the programme coordinators and lecturing staff will be based on both sites to coordinate the programme. The details per site have not been provided. As per the annexure\'2C a Diploma \'2F Degree in Business Administration is the minimum qualification required. It is not clear how someone with a Business Administration qualification will provide adequate leadership on an IT programme. The reason has not been addressed.\line \line 4.5 Technical support\'3A\line \line The Institution did not explain the technical support\'3B instead\'2C it focused on administrative duties and reporting. The reason has not been addressed.\line \line 4.6 Administrative support staff\'3A\line \line The Institution has referred to Annexure L\'2C which has listed and described some administrative support functions that include qualification coordinator\'2C support administrator\'2C customer hero\'2C and examination administrator. It was indicated that  there is a coordinator at each site. However\'2C it is not clear if other support services are at each site or at the Midrand campus where the programme is managed by the HOD.\line \line 5.1 Roles and responsibilities\'3A\line \line On the lack of clarity regarding the roles and responsibilities of e-tutors\'2C lecturers and facilitators\'2C the Institution has provided an annexure. There is a description of responsibilities of the three positions referred to in the reason for non-accreditation. However\'2C e-tutors and facilitators are not regarded as employees or staff members of the Institution\'2C but as independent contractors who can provide their own facilities such a computer\'2C internet access\'2C workspace\'2C and any other office-related equipment. At the same time\'2C e-tutors may be required to mark students\'E2\'80\'99 assignments and examinations\'2C and this will be specified in an independent task agreement with its own remuneration. The role of e-tutors as independent contractors and their appointment requirements have to be clarified. The reason has not been adequately addressed.\line \line 5.2 Teaching at both sites\'3A\line \line The Institution referred to an annexure that was not attached. The reason has not been met.\line \line 5.3 At-risk students\'3A\line \line The Institution has indicated that at-risk students are identified after the score of an at-risk questionnaire conducted each term. The use of a questionnaire is not a known appropriate mechanism for identifying at-risk students. Normally\'2C students are regarded at risk after a review of assessments\'2C not a questionnaire. In this regard\'2C the Institution does not have an appropriate process for identifying at-risk students. The reason has not been addressed.\line \line 6.1 Formative and summative assessment\'3A\line \line The Institution remains unclear on assessment. In the Application Programming APPR211 subject guide\'2C the formative assessment counts 50\'25 and summative assessment counts 50\'25. In the same subject guide\'2C the Institution allocates 10\'25 to continuous assessment\'2C 20\'25 to venue-based and\'2For online-proctored semester test\'2C 20\'25 to individual assignment\'2C and 50\'25 is allocated to venue-based and\'2For online-proctored examination. The assessment structure above is not specific on the types of assessment tools used to assess students. The reason has not been met.\line \line 6.2 Weighting of assessment\'3A\line \line The Institution has amended the weightings of the modules in subject forms. The change mentioned is 50\'25 for formative assessment and 50\'25 for summative assessment. The formative assessments cannot have the same level of challenge as the summative assessments. Therefore\'2C they cannot be allocated the same weight. The reason has not been met. \line \line 6.3 Method of assessment in module outlines\'3A\line \line The information that the Institution referred to has not been provided. The reason has not been adequately addressed. In the subject forms\'2C the Institution has indicated that continuous assessment counts 10\'25\'3B continuous assessment is not a method of assessment required. The Institution has allocated 20\'25 weight to the venue-based and\'2For online-proctored semester test and 50\'25 to venue-based and\'2For online-proctored examination\'2C while 20\'25 is allocated to individual assignment.\line \line 6.4 Lack of clarity on summative exams\'3A\line \line In response\'2C the Institution has indicated that the final mark composition has been clarified in the new learner guides to be a 3-hour venue-based or online-proctored examination. The submission indicates that this programme will be offered as a contact mode programme. There is still no clarity on the online and venue-based exams. The reason has not been met.\line \line 6.5 Assessment and moderation policies\'3A\line \line The Institution has indicated that its assessment and moderation policies were reviewed\'2C and reference is made to Annexures N and O. Annexure N is not applicable to moderation and assessment\'3B it is about student guidance and support. The moderation policy is incomplete - it does not refer to the qualifications of moderators and the duration of their contracts. If policy is in place\'2C it is not clear why the HOD is responsible for granting supplementary examinations. The reason has not been met.\line \line 6.6 Supplementary examinations\'3A\line \line Insufficient information has been provided. It is not clear if students will be allowed to write the supplementary examinations for all the subjects with 40-49\'25 or for a specific number of subjects.The reason has not been met.\line \line 6.7 Processing of results\'3A\line \line The Institution has mentioned that the assessment and moderation policies have been updated\'2C and include the processes to ensure the validity of results and processing of results. It is the responsibility of the examinations officer to ensure marks are captured correctly. In relation to assessment\'2C the Assessment Policy states that the assessor has to record the results of the assessment in compliance with requirements of the department and Institution. The policy needs to be clear as to who captures the marks on the system and how. The reason has not been adequately addressed.\line \line 7.1 Venues for practical\'3A\line \line The Institution did not provide any additional evidence regarding the insufficient practical class venues. It has\'2C however\'2C indicated that\'2C upon enrolment\'2C students will be issued with a laptop with the required software installed. The software will be provided to students who opt to purchase their own laptops. The Institution needs to clarify in its marketing material that students will have to buy their own laptop with the minimum specifications. The reason has not been met.\line \line 7.2 Library facilities\'3A\line \line In addition to online resources\'2C such as EBSCOHost and Perlego\'2C there is a librarian and an assistant to help students. There are at least three copies of each prescribed textbook and one copy of each recommended textbook available. Each student will have a laptop. It needs to be verified that the library and required resources are available for student use. \line \line 7.3 Network infrastructure\'3A\line \line On the evidence for network or cybersecurity labs\'2C the Institution has again mentioned the issuing of laptops to students with the specifications of the laptops. All the practical sessions of networking cannot be done online using simulated activities. Therefore\'2C the lack of appropriate labs\'2C mostly for network specialisation\'2C challenges the expectation that the purpose of the programme will be met. \line \line 7.4 Equipped classrooms\'3A\line \line There is no evidence of the availability of equipment in the classroom. The Institution has indicated that there will be a desktop computer for guest lecturers in addition to HDMI and VGA cables for connection to the projector. \line \line 7.5 Exam venues\'3A\line \line The Institution did not submit any supporting evidence on the existence of examination venues. However\'2C there is mention of using the same lecturing venues for assessment. This statement would require verification during a site visit as it is not clear if these venues are conducive for assessment. The Institution has also mentioned that\'2C for distance learning\'2C examinations will be online. The programme applied for is not a distance learning programme. The reason has not been met.\line \line 7.6 Specific computers\'3A\line \line Upon enrolment\'2C students are issued with a laptop with the required software or they may purchase their own laptops for which the software will be provided. The Institution has provided the minimum technical specifications for the hardware such as 8GB RAM and 2GB Graphics Card. The reason has been met.\line \line 7.7 Resources for practical work\'3A\line \line The Institution has indicated that it will issue laptops and specifications for these laptops have been provided. However\'2C the laptop will not be sufficient for all the practical needs\'2C especially for the students specialising in Network and Security. These students will need physical network laboratories to learn how to connect the computers in a network environment and provide support. These practical sessions cannot be provided using online demonstrations. The reason has not been met.\line \line 8.1 System information\'3A\line \line The Institution mentions that its system is integrated with NetSuite ERP which manages the finance and sales side of operations. For students\'2C the myAIE Student Portal is used as a Management Information System for storing all student data with cloud access. There is a need to verify the available MIS system\'2C administration systems\'2C and student portal on how these meet stakeholders\'E2\'80\'99 needs. The reason has not been adequately addressed.\line \line 8.2 Administrative services\'3A\line \line The activities mentioned cannot be done in one system. Usually teaching and learning systems are separated from administrative systems for security and flexibility - one cannot have one system perform all the mentioned activities. Therefore\'2C it is recommended that the available MIS system\'2C administration systems\'2C and student portal are verified on how they meet stakeholders\'E2\'80\'99 needs. \line \line 8.3 Information fields\'3A\line \line The Institution has indicated that it captures various fields on the system pertaining to students such as demographics\'2C nationality\'2C contact information\'2C account payer information\'2C class attendance and assessment results. It can draw reports on students\'27 grades\'2C attendance\'2C academic history\'2C etc. There is a need to verify the existing systems and the reports produced by the systems. \line \line 8.4 MIS and marks\'3A\line \line The MIS is about marking the online assessments completed by the students. This view of the MIS reflects the challenge of the Institution in its MIS\'2C administrative system\'2C and student portal as it cannot relate the support provided by the MIS to its activities. The reason has not been met.\line \line 8.5 Sign-off on students\'27 marks\'3A\line \line The response indicates that assessments are done online\'2C and the Institution is not fully responding to the requirement. The signing-off on marks is a form of authority on marking. If each campus is independent\'2C the site could have signed off its marks\'2C which is different to sign-off that happens after marking. Therefore\'2C the Institution did not clarify the responsibility for final sign-off on students\'E2\'80\'99 marks. The reason has not been met.\line \line The Directorate recommends that the programme should not be accredited.\cell \pard 

